description:
Auby-les-Hesdin was the location of a major supply depot on the western front during the Great War. According to historical records this supply hub and the railways in the area were manned and maintained almost exclusively by the CLC.

the Chinese Labour Corps - Although China would officially declare war on Germany in 1917 after a German torpedo sunk a ship carrying chinese civillians, a considerable number of Chinese citizens had already been involved in non-belligerant roles since 1916 through the Chinese Labour Corps (CLC). Around 140.000 men were enlisted, mostly poor farmhands from northern China and younger students to serve as translators. The CLC performed grueling jobs in harsh conditions for little to no pay in the rear lines: building and repairing roads and railways, unloading cargo from ships and trains, building fortifications, digging trenches, filling sandbags, constructing munitions depots and other such tasks were their main focus.
The CLC's significant contribution was barely recognised at the end of the conflict.; The men of the Labour Corps were, in fact, denied te right to settle or receive citizenship. Even today their memory remains mostly erased: of the circa 40,000 British Great War memorials not one remembers the deeds of the CLC.

"Bapaume" refers to a French town in the current-day region of Hauts-de-France, near the Belgian border. Bapaume finds itself in a strategically valuable position: the town sits on the border between the Flanders plains and the flatlands north of Paris.
 During the great war Bapaume was considered a strategic location and it exchanged hands many times; Captured by the advancing German army in 1914, it was then retaken by the British in 1917 in the context of the Battle of the Somme. In early 1918 Bapaume was recaptured by the Kaiser's army, only to finally fall back into entente hands a few months later.

the bombing of town hall - in March 1917 the retreating Germans rigged Bapaume town hall with several explosive devices. One of such devices would be missed by British sweeps of the building, and the delayed explosion caused the death of 24 people including Australian soldiers, Australian civillians, and 2 deputies of the French Parliament.

The Battle of Gnila Lipa saw the Austro-Hungarian and Russian armies engaged in fighting on the eastern front, more precisely in area of the Gnila Lipa river in eastern Galicia. The battle took place during the first stages of the great war on 30 August 1914. An entire sector of the front was left unmanned by the Austro-Hungarians, the missing army either still deployed in the balkans or on its way on the slow imperial railway network. The Russians exploited this pushing west and scoring a decisive victory in the first months of the conflict.

Starting off as a limited effort by the German imperial army to relieve pressure on the Austro-Hungarian divisions to the south, the Gorlice-Tarnów offensive became the core of the Central Powers' advance in 1915 causing a momentary yet significant collapse of the Russian lines on the eastern front. The operation started on 1 May with the Germans and Astro-Hungarians heavily shelling the poorly-fortified Russian positions, followed by infantry advancements that, in some cases, completely destroyed Russian divisions. By 6 May according to August von Mackensen's comment "Along the entire line from the Vistula far into the Carpathians, the enemy is retreating". More and more successful advances from the Central Powers caused the Russian armies to completely retreat from Galicia, the offensive officialy drawing to a close in October due to unfavourable weather conditions.

the galician oil fields - Although a fairly undeveloped region of the empire, Galicia was the Central Powers' only domestic oil-producing region. The wells around Borysław fueled the empire both in peace and war times. The Geman navy also heavily relied on Galician oil, which made the victory scored in battle of Gorlice-Tarnów very consequential to the continuation of marine warfare in the North Sea.

In 1917 the German army launched the last major offensive operation on the eastern front: the Battle of Riga, a.k.a. the Battle of Jugla, after the river that flows near the city. 
The plan was to put pressure on the northern sector of the eastern front and threaten the Russian capital Petrograd forcing Russia to accept a peace treaty. On 1 September German divisions started moving towards Riga, splitting in two groups: the first would march north to the city, the second one would intercept Russian foces along the Jugla river. Most of the fighting occured in the vicinity of the Jugla, while the first group entered Riga almost without resistance since the Russians had time to retreat.
Although the casualties were minimal on both sides, the battle was a success for the Central Powers, that now threatened the Russian empire's industrial core.
The Battle of Jugla was followed by Operation Albion, an amphibious assault on several isles in the Baltic Sea. The in-game map "Albion" takes place during this offensive.

The Battle of Lutsk was the opening battle of the Brusilov offensive, a major counterattack by Russian forces in the summer of 1916. The battle itself started on 4 June 1916 with artillery bombardment over the Austro-Hungarian defences opening gaps in the barbed wire fortifications. After the shelling, which lasted several hours, the infantry started its advance, often catching Austro-Hungarian soldiers by surprise and either capturing them without a fight or prompting a chaotic retreat. The Central Powers' forces tried minor counterattcks to no avail: in just a handful of days around 130.000 men were either captured, dead, or MIA. The result of this battle even convinced Romania to join the war on the side of the Entente.
The Brusilov offensive continued beyond the Battle of Lutsk, eventually losing momentum and stopping in September.

skin: Battle of the Strait of Otranto

description:
William Lendrum Mitchell (a.k.a. Billy Mitchell) was a general in the United States Army during the Great War. After the USA joined the war in April 1917 Mitchell started to conduct air operations over the western front, quickly gaining experience and a reputation for his fearless and unconventional leadership. It was his flamboyant and daring behaviour that antagonised many in the US Army General Staff, setting him up for a troubled carreer after the war's end.
In 1918 he planned and led the air detachement of the Battle of Saint-Mihiel.
Mitchell is also known for his role as a strong proponent of naval aviation tactics in the inter-war period.

Camouflage in the great war - The Great War saw the birth of modern military Camouflage. All entente and central power nations entered the war with felt, cotton, or wool uniforms that would turn out to be inappropriate for a ever-evolving battlefield. Infantry uniforms and equipment were in a particular sorry state at the outbreak of the war: 
- The French army sported the "Pantalon Rouge" uniform: a blue coat with bright red trousers; Hardly a Camouflage for the fields of the western front.
- The majority of the soldiers on the Austro-Italian front were outfitted with thin wool uniforms unfit for alpine combat.
- Headgear for most armies was either absent or unable to protect the wearer against the ever-present risk of shrapnel.
With the advent of air warfare concealing troops and vehicles from aerial reconnaissance was becoming a priority: paintjobs like the German Buntfarbenanstrich 1918 were used in later stages of the war. (more below)

Air, sea, and ground vehicles also made use of Camouflage. Some battleships were painted with a dazzle pattern, designed to disrupt the ship's silhouette and make it harder to estimate direction and movement speed. For the same reasons some planes used lozenge patterns in which tightly-tiled colourful polygons "blur" the aircraft's shape. Completely different was the case of "The Flying Circus", the Red Baron's flying unit whose planes were brightly coloured.

The Battle of the Crna Bend was a significant engagement between Entente and Central Power forces on the Macedonian front during the Great War. Part of the spring offensive of 1917, the battle saw French, Italian, and Russian divisions attack the extremely well fortified Bulgarian and German positions along the bend of the Crna river. The attack, designed to break the stalling balkan front, was successfully repelled by the Central Powers' armies despite being numerically and materially at a disadvantage, ensuring the integrity of the Macedonian front not only in 1917, but up until the end of the war.

The Battle of Doberdò was an Italian offensive part of the 6th battle of the Isonzo. The fighting took place between the Italians and Austro-Hungarians, though mostly Hungarians and Slovenes made up the imperial ranks.
Before the battle some Austrian divisions were moved away from the Italian front to reinforce elsewhere, prompting Italian generals to order an attack with the objective to seize the village of Doberdò and the main road leading to the city of Gorizia to the south. The Italians split in two, with one section attacking the defensive lines head-on and the other flanking them. The infantry whose orders was to attack from the front faced machinegun fire and chemical weapons, yet after huge losses managed to break the Austro-Hungarian line wherefrom the enemy couldn't retreat because of the flanking army that engaged them, sometimes even in fierce hand-to-hand combat. Although a strategically valuable victory for the Kingdom of Italy, the battle inflicted heavy casualties on both sides.

"F-Patrone" probably refers to a more obscure version of the 7,92x57mm Mauser cartridge used by the German army during the Great War. The standard 7,92x57mm cartirdge was adopted by the German Empire in 1903 and would become the standard-issue ammunition for both world wars.
The 7.92x57mm Mauser is fired not only by the MG15 n.A., but also other weapons available in-game such as the General Liu Rifle, Madsen MG, and others.
Not much is known about the F-version of this cartridge; It was probably only used in the last weeks of the war.

Giuseppe was and still is a fairly common proper male name in Italy. It would've been absolutely possible to meet quite a few Giuseppes on all fronts where soldiers from the Kingdom of Italy were deployed.
Perhaps the most famous Italian bearing this name who fought in the Great War is the poet Giuseppe Ungaretti, whose works about life in the trenches are still appreciated to this day for their gritty yet poetic realism.

misspelling - The in-game text is misspelled "Guiseppe" instead of "Giuseppe". This mistake is very common among English native speakers; Just on the BBC's website around 1000 occurrences of this misspelled name can be found. The origins of this ortographical error are not known, although some speculate it might have some relations to the stereotype of the "Guido" among Italian immigrants,.

The Hanyang Arsenal was a Chinese arsenal, established in 1891 by Quing officials in Hanyang county, after which it is named. 
The arsenal made use of local resources such as coal and steel to produce rifles and field guns. These weapons found their way into the hands of the Boxers during the 1900 rebellion and contributed to the success of the Wuchang uprising which would lead to the end of the Quing dynasty in 1912.
After the Great War the Hanyang Arsenal started producing copies of weapons used in the conflict like the Browning M1917 and the Mauser C96. The arsenal was also involved in the production of General Liu rifle prototypes, the project never seeing completion due to the death of General Liu and the loss of the equipment and machine tools necessary for production in an accident at sea.

Kulja, today known as Yining, is a city in the far western Xinjiang region of China. It was in this city that the Treaty of Kulja was signed in 1851 between the Russian Empire and the Qing Empire. The treaty opened the western Chinese cities of Kulja and Chuguchak to Russian trade, symbolising  the growing Russian influence in central Asia, whereas Chinese military defences were becoming neglected and outdated.

Espionage operations were carried out fairly frequently during the Great War aiming to thwart enemy schemes, conceal ongoing domestic plans, or sabotage the enemy home front. At the outbreak of the war neutral countries became hubs for spies from both sides; This was the case of the neutral Netherlands.
"Mata Hari" was the stage name of Margaretha Geertruida Zelle, a Dutch exotic dancer and courtesan. Before the war she was known for her promiscuous and flirtatious performances, embodying the idea of the bohemian artist, ofter performing in the nude and only wearing bejeweled breastplates and headwear.
Being a Dutch citizen Zelle was allowed to travel freely, yet never too close to the front. When she asked to meet her lover, a Russian general fighting for the Entente on the western front whom she had seduced, after he was wounded in battle, Zelle was approached by the Deuxième Bureau, the French intelligence agency, with an offer to spy on the German crown prince Wilhelm and report any valuable military intelligence. She accepted to spy for the French, but in a metting with a German attaché in neutral Madrid she allegedly agreed to be a double-agent for the Germans.
The Deuxiéme Bureau caught wind of Zelle's turning through an intercepted communication, and once it could be confirmed she was arrested in Paris. Zelle was put on trial, although neither the British nor the French could produce reliable evidence of her betrayal. Zelle allegedly defended herself while on trial: "A harlot? Yes, but a traitoress, never!".
The trial of "Mata Hari" was complicated and animated by war politics, and although she presumably never confessed, Zelle was executed by firing squad on 15 October 1917.

Helmuth Johann Ludwig von Moltke (a.k.a. Moltke the younger) was a German general whose role in the Great War, specifically in the Marne campaign, is as important as it is controversial.
Born in 1848, Moltke was named after his uncle Helmuth Karl Bernhard von Moltke, a hero of the German reunification wars. After becoming Chief of the German Great General Staff in 1906 he reviewed and approved Von Schlieffen's plans.
At the start of the war Moltke found himself having to deal with both the western and the eastern front, an almost impossible task that caused many of his contemporaries and later historians to blame him for the unsuccessful Marne campaign. It was during this campaign that Moltke the younger's health would start deteriorating, leading to his resignation in September 1914 in favour of Erich von Falkenhayn and his death in 1916.

Noyelles-sur-Mer is a small town in northern France home to a major British rear base during the Great War. Nearly 12,000 members of the CLC were housed at Auby-les-Hesdin.
The conditions in the camp were harsh for the Chinese labourers who faced strict military discipline, grueling hours and exhausting manual labour. The town was first struck by a cholera outbreak and later on by the Spanish flu. Many labourers lost their lives to these diseases. 
The CLC represented the first big wave of Chinese immigration in France. Today in Noyelles-sur-Mer the Chinese cemetery still exists; Although most of the graves bear no name, the site means to honor the sacrifice of the Chinese Labour Corps.

Oigee was a optics manufacturer based in Berlin. They mainly produced binoculars and weapon scopes and optics.

weapon sights - During the war a good number of weapons were outfitted with optics such as single-action rifles and machineguns. This is represented in-game with some weapon variants such as the suppressive and marksman variants.

"Over There" was an American propaganda song composed by George M. Cohan in 1917; for his work on this and later propaganda songs Cohan was awarded the Congressional Gold Medal.
The song was meant to inspire confidence in the good outcome of the war for the USA and galvanise young American men to enlist to fight in the Great War and by 1918 more than 2 million copies of sheet music were sold.
Later conflicts like the second world war, the Vietnam war, and even the more recent war on terror saw a resurgence of this song; A testament to its relevance in American culture.

The kings and emperors of the Great War often ruled by decree. Parliamentary monarchy was by far the most widespread political system in Europe and elsewhere at the time of the Great War, making royal edicts, statutes, orders, and decrees quite common.
Most famous among these wartime decrees is the United Kingdom's Defence of the Realm Act (DORA). This act legalised the requisition of buildings and lands for the war effort, made it illegal to "spread reports likely to cause disaffection or alarm among any of His Majesty's forces or among the civilian population, and introduced of a list of prohibited activities such as flying kites, lighting bonfires, and buying binoculars.
Royal edicts were also issued for matters such as declarations of war and the establishment of military honours and medals.

Augusta Taurinorum was the name given by the Romans to the modern-day settlement of Turin, in northern Italy. Turin had always been an industrial city and during the Great War the city's factories contributed to the war effort. 
At the outbreak of the war most of Turin's population held anti-interverntionists views. It is no wonder that in the summer of 1917, after seeing many young men conscripted, the prices of food skyrocket, and even the city's great theater converted into ammunition depot, the city erupted in one of Italy's biggest anti-war revolt which left around 60 dead and 200 injured.

Hummingbids are birds of the Trochilidae biological family. They are known for their bright iridescent colours, the humming sound their wings make when flying, and, most famously, their small size. Hummingbirds are in fact the smallest known bird family in the world, just like the Kolibri (German for Hummingbird) pistol fires the smallest centerfire cartridge ever produced: the 2.7x9mm Kolibri.

Silvio Scaroni was an Italian flying ace during the Great War. Scaroni took part in many air operations on the Italian front, scoring 30 victories, 26 of which officially confirmed, flying French-designed Caudron planes.
During an air raid on Austro-Hungarian artillery in the proximity of Doberdò Scaroni's plane was hit by an anti-air gun whose shrapnels pierced the engine, stalling the plane and spilling boiling engine oil on the plane's two occupants. Regardless, Scaroni was able to perform an emergency landing and was later awarded the bronze medal of military valor.
After the Great War Scaroni's experience as a pilot and air advisor was then put to use in Chiang Kai-Shek's China, only returning in Italy after the outbreak of the Second Sino-Japanese war.
His role as air commander for Sicily during the second world war put him at odds with Herrmann Göring, a professional conflict which cost him his job.

Luftschiffbau Schütte-Lanz was an aircraft manufacturer operating before, during, and shortly after the Great War. Schütte-Lanz mainly produced airships, although smaller production lines for automobiles and military planes were set up at different times in the manufacturing plant in Brühl.
The company was the main competitor of the more famous Luftschiffbau Zeppelin, perhaps lagging behind them because of their outdated airship designs that used wooden frames instead of duralumin frames.
The treaty of Versailles imposed harsh restriction on German aircraft production and as a consequence Schütte-Lanz went out of business in 1925.

Thingumyjig is what is called a "placeholder name". Placeholder names are used to identify something or someone without a specific name or whose name is temporarily forgotten. Some examples of placeholder names are: John/Jane Doe (USA), Thingamabob (UK), Max/Erika Mustermann (Germany).

"Toward the Flame" refers to the war memoir written by the American writer Hervey Allen in 1926.
Allen fought in the 28th division, an American combat unit mostly made up of Pennsylvania National guardsmen, and took part in fighting on the western front.
The memoir spares no details in telling the story of Allen's experience, focusing in particular on the disastrous Battle of Fismettes and the controversial military actions that took place during the battle. "Toward the Flame" stands as both a very relevant historical document and a beautifully-narrated piece of literature.
